@node "programm" "c00LTeXT - Introduction"

                         @{u}@{b}What is it for?@{uu}@{ub}

c00LTeXT is a small program capable of either giving normal ASCII texts a
cool look or making them VERY unreadable. If you can't anything in the
output file you should consider to read the chapter @{"usage" link "benutzung"}...

If you don't know where is is about now take a look at this example of
how it could look (depends on the configuration):

                 --------------------------------------

©00l7EX7 iS a SMALl pr0GRam ©APaßLE 0f EI7HeR giViNg n0rMAl As©iI 7ex7s a
©00l L00k 0R mAking 7hem vERy unReaDaßLe. if y0u ©an'7 aNY7HInG IN 7He
0u7pU7 fiLE y0U Sh0uld ©0nsider 70 reAd 7HE ©hap7er Usage...

If Y0U D0N'7 KN0w whERe iS Is Aß0u7 N0w 7aKe a l00K a7 7his EXAmple 0F
H0w I7 ©0ulD L00K:

                 --------------------------------------

@{i}'OK, looks cool, but why on earth I shoud use c00LTeXT? There are other
programs doing the same job!'@{ui} That's right, but there are some reasons for
using c00LTeXT:

1. It's written by me ;-)
2. You already own it...
3. You can control the way of converting by both a prefs-file and options
@endnode
@node "install" "c00LTeXT - Installation"

                              @{u}@{b}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

To install c00LTeXT to your harddisk, please copy the following files to it:

  c00LTeXT        - should be located in c:
  c00LTeXT.prefs  - has to be in env:
  c00LTeXT.Guide  - copy it anywhere you want

When using the DOS/CLI/Shell, you should type the following lines (if the
directory of c00LTeXT is 'ram:c00LTeXT'):

cd ram:c00LTeXT/
copy c00LTeXT c:
copy c00LTeXT.prefs env:
copy c00LTeXT.prefs envarc:
copy c00LTeXT-E.Guide help: (or any other directory)

That's all, c00LTeXT is ready to run now!
@endnode
@node "hard" "c00LTeXT - Requirements"

                                 @{u}@{b}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

This program should run on any Amiga (or compatible computer :) equipped
with AmigaOS V2.0 or better. It was only tested on my own machine yet:

  Amiga 1200 T
  Blizzard 1260, 50 MHz
  2 MB Chipram, 24 MB Fastram
  Kickstart 3.1
  340 MB, 1,2 GB Harddisk
  CD-Rom: 4xSpeed

If c00LTeXT doesn't run on your system, please drop @{"me" link "autor"} a line,
don't forget to write down your configuration and the problem (e.g. a Guru
number).
@endnode
@node "benutzung" "c00LTeXT - Usage"

                             @{u}@{b}Usage@{uu}@{ub}


@{u}@{b}The prefs file@{uu}@{ub}

There are two methods of controllin the way c00LTeXT modifies the text.
At first, you can use a preferences file to specify the chars to be replaced
by other ones. This file has to be named 'env:c00LTeXT'. If you have located
env: in the ram disk, please copy it also to envarc:, otherwise it will not
survive a reset. c00LTeXT needs the keyword 'c00LTeXT' in the first line
of the file to be sure this document is really a prefs-file. This keyword
has to be case-sensitive!! All following lines should consist of two chars
each, the first one is to be replaced by the second one. Bevor writing a
own preferences file please have a look at the example, or just modify the
one which came with this archive.

Example:

                      -------------------------------
c00LTeXT
o0
O0
c©
C©
r®
R®
Bß
bß
t7
T7
                      -------------------------------

As you can see this file would replace all 'o's by '0' (both small and
capital letters), 'c' by '©' and so on...


@{u}@{b}Options@{uu}@{ub}

You can use some command line options to set the method small and capital
letters are converted. It doesn't make any sense to use two or more of them,
in this case only the first one will be used.

-n (normal):     Doesn't change anything (Example - Example)
-i (inverted):   Inverts the text, i.e. all capital letters are replaced by
                 small ones and inversely (Example - eXAMPLE)
-l (lower case): Converts all chars to upper case (Example - example)
-u (upper case): Converts all chars to lower case (Example - EXAMPLE)
-m (mixed):      Randomly converts letters to either small or capital ones
                 (Example - eXAmPlE)

If you don't use one of this options, -m will be used.
@endnode
